ules compose at an application boundary."},"154":{"id":"/docs/guides/examples-24","page_id":"/docs/guides/examples","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/examples#convert-one-unreliable-boundary-into-a-tuple","content":"Good tuple code usually starts at an edge: HTTP, files, subprocesses, validation, IPC, or user-provided data."},"155":{"id":"/docs/guides/examples-25","page_id":"/docs/guides/examples","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/examples#fetch-json-with-a-real-deadline","content":"The timeout and parent `signal` are linked, so either one can stop the request."},"156":{"id":"/docs/guides/examples-26","page_id":"/docs/guides/examples","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/examples#retry-only-the-noisy-dependency","content":"Avoid retrying the whole route handler. Validation, authorization, and side effects should not run again just because a remote service had a brief wobble."},"157":{"id":"/docs/guides/examples-27","page_id":"/docs/guides/examples","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/examples#reuse-a-schedule-policy","content":"Schedules are useful when several call sites should share timing rules without sharing business logic."},"158":{"id":"/docs/guides/examples-28","page_id":"/docs/guides/examples","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/examples#put-a-ceiling-on-a-shared-resource","content":"Use semaphores for \"only N at once.\" Use rate limiters for \"only N per time window.\""},"159":{"id":"/docs/guides/examples-29","page_id":"/docs/guides/examples","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/examples#respect-an-api-quota","content":"Keeping the wait explicit makes quota pressure visible in code review."},"160":{"id":"/docs/guides/examples-30","page_id":"/docs/guides/examples","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/examples#hand-work-from-producers-to-workers","content":"Bound the queue when producers can outpace workers. Capacity is part of the user experience."},"161":{"id":"/docs/guides/examples-31","page_id":"/docs/guides/examples","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/examples#broadcast-local-progress","content":"Use pub/sub for in-process progress, notifications, and diagnostics. Use durable infrastructure when events must survive restarts."},"162":{"id":"/docs/guides/examples-32","page_id":"/docs/guides/examples","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/examples#cache-stable-reads","content":"Cache reads, not commands. Failed loads are returned but not stored."},"163":{"id":"/docs/guides/examples-33","page_id":"/docs/guides/examples","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/examples#batch-nearby-keyed-reads","content":"Batchers return one value per requested key, in the same order. If your backend returns unordered results, map them back explicitly."},"164":{"id":"/docs/guides/examples-34","page_id":"/docs/guides/examples","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/examples#fail-fast-when-a-dependency-is-already-down","content":"Circuit breakers are for external dependencies and expensive boundaries, not validation branches."},"165":{"id":"/docs/guides/examples-35","page_id":"/docs/guides/examples","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/examples#make-async-tests-deterministic","content":"Manual clocks work best when the production code accepts a clock or sleep dependency. They do not patch global timers."},"166":{"id":"/docs/guides/examples-36","page_id":"/docs/guides/examples","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/examples#a-user-card-loader","content":"This example validates input, fetches two independent resources under one cancellation signal, and returns an ordinary view model."},"167":{"id":"/docs/guides/examples-37","page_id":"/docs/guides/examples","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/examples#a-user-card-loader","content":"The two fetches are allowed to run together, but a failure in either one aborts the other."},"168":{"id":"/docs/guides/examples-38","page_id":"/docs/guides/examples","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/examples#a-cached-graphql-style-resolver-helper","content":"This example combines `cache` and `batcher`: repeated IDs are cached across resolver calls, while nearby misses are batched together."},"169":{"id":"/docs/guides/examples-39","page_id":"/docs/guides/examples","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/examples#a-cached-graphql-style-resolver-helper","content":"The batcher removes N+1 pressure from the current tick. The cache removes repeated reads across later calls."},"170":{"id":"/docs/guides/examples-40","page_id":"/docs/guides/examples","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/examples#a-product-route-with-cached-reads-and-explicit-fresh-reload","content":"The caller can ask for freshness without bypassing the tuple flow or duplicating the loader."},"171":{"id":"/docs/guides/examples-41","page_id":"/docs/guides/examples","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/examples#a-webhook-intake-route-that-returns-quickly","content":"The webhook handler validates and enqueues. The slow reconciliation work can happen in a worker with retries, logging, and its own cancellation boundary."},"172":{"id":"/docs/guides/examples-42","page_id":"/docs/guides/examples","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/examples#avoid-hiding-every-policy-in-one-wrapper","content":"This makes the code look compact, but now readers must learn your runtime before they can understand a request."},"173":{"id":"/docs/guides/examples-43","page_id":"/docs/guides/examples","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/examples#avoid-hiding-every-policy-in-one-wrapper","content":"Prefer visible composition at the boundary:"},"174":{"id":"/docs/guides/examples-44","page_id":"/docs/guides/examples","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/examples#avoid-using-queues-as-silent-memory","content":"If the input is user-sized or service-sized, make the pressure visible:"},"175":{"id":"/docs/guides/examples-45","page_id":"/docs/guides/examples","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/ex